<edge source="st.ii-ii.q104.a001" target="concept.obedience" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q104.a001.treated_in.concept.obedience">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q104.a001.treated_in.concept.obedience</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q104.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.104 a.1 — Is one man bound to obey another?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.obedience</data>
  <data key="d12">Obedience</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q104-a001-treated-in-concept-obedience-st-ii-ii-q104-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q104.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Just as the actions of natural things proceed from natural powers, so do human actions proceed from the human will. On natural things it behooved the higher to move the lower to their actions by the excellence of the natural power bestowed on them by God : and</data>
  <data key="d18"></data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q104.a001" target="concept.superior_role" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q104.a001.treated_in.concept.superior_role">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q104.a001.treated_in.concept.superior_role</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q104.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.104 a.1 — Is one man bound to obey another?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.superior_role</data>
  <data key="d12">Superior Role</data>
  <data key="d13">role</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q104-a001-treated-in-concept-superior-role-st-ii-ii-q104-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q104.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">e higher, so too in human affairs, in virtue of the order of natural and divine law , inferiors are bound to obey their superiors.</data>
  <data key="d18"></data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
