  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q106.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.106 a.2 — Who owes more thanks to God, the innocent or the penitent?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.benefaction</data>
  <data key="d12">Benefaction</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q106-a002-treated-in-concept-benefaction-st-ii-ii-q106-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q106.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Thanksgiving [gratiarum actio] in the recipient corresponds to the favor [gratia] of the giver: so that when there is greater favor on the part of the giver, greater thanks are due on the part of the recipient. Now a favor is someth</data>
  <data key="d18"></data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
