<edge source="st.ii-ii.q106.a003" target="concept.benefactor_role" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q106.a003.treated_in.concept.benefactor_role">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q106.a003.treated_in.concept.benefactor_role</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q106.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.106 a.3 — Is man always bound to give thanks for human favors?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.benefactor_role</data>
  <data key="d12">Benefactor Role</data>
  <data key="d13">role</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q106-a003-treated-in-concept-benefactor-role-st-ii-ii-q106-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q106.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">He is the cause of all": for the effect must needs always be directed to the end of the agent. Now it is evident that a benefactor, as such, is cause of the beneficiary. Hence the natural order requires that he who has received a favor should, by repaying the favor, turn to his benefactor</data>
  <data key="d18"></data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q106.a003" target="concept.gratitude" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q106.a003.treated_in.concept.gratitude">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q106.a003.treated_in.concept.gratitude</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q106.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.106 a.3 — Is man always bound to give thanks for human favors?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.gratitude</data>
  <data key="d12">Gratitude</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q106-a003-treated-in-concept-gratitude-st-ii-ii-q106-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q106.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Every effect turns naturally to its cause ; wherefore Dionysius says (Div. Nom. i) that " God turns all things to Himself because He is the cause of all": for the effect must needs always be directed to the end of the agent. Now it is evident that a benefactor</data>
  <data key="d18"></data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q106.a003" target="concept.honor" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q106.a003.treated_in.concept.honor">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q106.a003.treated_in.concept.honor</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q106.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.106 a.3 — Is man always bound to give thanks for human favors?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.honor</data>
  <data key="d12">Honor</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q106-a003-treated-in-concept-honor-st-ii-ii-q106-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q106.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">of each. And, as stated above with regard to a father ( II-II:31:3 ; II-II:101:2 ), a man owes his benefactor, as such, honor and reverence, since the latter stands to him in the relation of principle; but accidentally he owes him assistance or support, if he need it.</data>
  <data key="d18"></data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
